3. Copies of N.

This is the most numerous group of MSS„ and the majority possess a distinctive character, being apparently derived from a copy of the Black Book made by William Roper, chief clerk of the Queen's Bench (1523-1577), Sir Thomas More’s son-in-law. They usually contain an extract from Bale upon Gervase of Tilbury3 Memoranda ‘De Averiis pascendis,' &c.‚ from the Red Book3 and an Index Rerum.
